<subSubSection lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="228" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[686,1199,1391,1730]" box="[686,954,1568,1594]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis box="[686,954,1568,1594]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">Descriptive characters</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[686,1199,1391,1730]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">The hairs on the back are chestnut brown with slightly darker roots. On the underside, the tips are pale chestnut brown and the roots dark brown. Forearm length</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[130,643,163,1731]" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">
is 33.0– 
<quantity box="[227,336,163,190]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.66" pageId="23" pageNumber="228" unit="mm" value="36.6">36.6 mm</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[355,450,163,190]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="7.[130,143,167,188]" captionTargetId="graphics@7.[127,1200,376,1322]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 4. External and bacular measurements (in mm) and body mass (in g) of 21 species of Vespertilionidae recorded from Myanmar, including the lengths of head and body (HB), tail (TAIL), foot (HF), tibia (TIBIA), forearm (FA), fifth, fourth, third metacarpal (5MET, 4MET and 3MET), ear (E), and baculum (BAC LGT). Sample sizes for males and females differing from those reported under n are given in parentheses after the measurement. Mean and SD are included when sample size is 3 or more. Data in italics are based on specimens collected outside Myanmar. Species listed in order of genera, and taxonomic groups and subgroups based on Corbet and Hill (1992) and Bates and Harrison (1997)" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">Table 4</tableCitation>
, external meas- urements based on specimens from Viet- nam in 
<bibRefCitation author="BATES, P. J. J. &amp; D. L. HARRISON" bookContentInfo="258 pp." box="[224,440,232,259]" journalOrPublisher="Harrison Zoological Museum Publications, Sevenoaks" pageId="23" pageNumber="228" refId="ref20800" refString="BATES, P. J. J., and D. L. HARRISON. 1997. The bats of the Indian Subcontinent. Harrison Zoological Museum Publications, Sevenoaks, 258 pp." title="The bats of the Indian Subcontinent" type="book" year="1997">
Bates 
<emphasis box="[299,360,232,258]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">et al.</emphasis>
, 1997
</bibRefCitation>
; FA = 34.2–37.0 mm in 
<bibRefCitation author="HENDRICHSEN, D. K. &amp; P. J. J. BATES &amp; B. D. HAYES &amp; J. L. WALSTON" box="[217,515,266,293]" journalOrPublisher="Myotis" pageId="23" pageNumber="228" pagination="35 - 122" part="39" refId="ref21801" refString="HENDRICHSEN, D. K., P. J. J. BATES, B. D. HAYES, and J. L. WALSTON. 2001. Recent records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Vietnam with six species new to the country. Myotis, 39: 35 - 122." title="Recent records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Vietnam with six species new to the country" type="journal article" year="2001">
Hendrichsen 
<emphasis box="[375,436,266,292]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">et al.</emphasis>
, 2001
</bibRefCitation>
). The fifth metacarpal is about equal in length to the third and fourth. The penis is not greatly enlarged. The baculum, based on an ex- tralimital specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[434,533,404,430]" name="Vietnam" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
is small, 
<quantity box="[130,228,438,465]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="23" pageNumber="228" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
in length, but robust. The shaft is curved downwards and is deeply grooved ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[261,360,507,533]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[130,143,1566,1587]" captionTargetBox="[142,1174,359,1543]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[126,1200,355,1552]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 1. Bacula of nine species of Pipistrellus, Arielulus and Ia. Lateral (above) and dorsal (below) views of: A — P. ceylonicus. HZM.3.31458, Sri Lanka; B — P. coromandra. MN2 (HZM.9.35441), Myanmar; C — P. tenuis. MV14 (HZM.11.35444), Myanmar; D — P. pulveratus. BD14, Myanmar; E — P. lophurus. After Hill and Harrison (1987); F — P. cadornae. HZM.3.32165, Vietnam; G — P. affinis. H22 (HZM.2.35125), Myanmar; H — A. circumdatus. After Hill and Harrison (1987); I — I. io. HZM.4.32150, Vietnam. Scale = 2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3942899" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3942899/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">Fig. 1F</figureCitation>
). There are two pro- nounced projections on each side of the base. The distal end is distinctively spoon- shaped. In the skull, the braincase is nar- row and rounded. The basioccipital area has a well defined central ridge running between the two cochleae but the basiocci- pital pits are virtually absent. The zygoma- ta are robust with a dorsal projection on each jugal bone. The second incisor (I3) at- tains the height of the secondary cusp of the first (I2) and is about equal in crown area. The first upper premolar (P2) is very small, about half or less the crown area of I2; it is situated in the recess formed by the upper canine (C1) and the second upper premolar (P4). The P2 of specimen BMNH.50.467 is minute, less than one quarter the crown area of I2. The first lower premolar (P2) is about two-thirds the crown area of the second (P4).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="228" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[130,643,163,1731]" box="[130,309,1262,1288]" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">
<emphasis box="[130,309,1262,1288]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">Similar species</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[130,643,163,1731]" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1916" box="[172,433,1296,1322]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cadornae">
<emphasis box="[172,433,1296,1322]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">Pipistrellus cadornae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="Keyserling &amp; Blasius, 1830" authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1871" box="[198,354,1330,1356]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Vesperugo" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pulveratus">
<emphasis box="[198,354,1330,1356]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">P. pulveratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1838" box="[419,563,1331,1356]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Scotophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="javanicus">
<emphasis box="[419,563,1331,1356]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">P. javanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its smaller first upper premolar (P2). The shape of the baculum is diagnostic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="228" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="23.[130,643,163,1731]" box="[130,226,1463,1489]" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">
<emphasis box="[130,226,1463,1489]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">Ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[130,643,163,1731]" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1916" box="[172,430,1498,1524]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cadornae">
<emphasis box="[172,430,1498,1524]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="228">Pipistrellus cadornae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected at 
<quantity box="[130,213,1532,1559]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.08" pageId="23" pageNumber="228" unit="m" value="708.0">708 m</quantity>
a.s.l. at Tasa Hku, where it was ‘caught in a banana tree in a jungle’. It was also found at 
<quantity box="[305,385,1601,1627]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.2" pageId="23" pageNumber="228" unit="m" value="920.0">920 m</quantity>
at Htinghnan in dry bamboo in ‘medium forest’ (information from the labels of specimens in The Natural History Museum, London).
</paragraph>
